metadata.name: Copenhagen Interpretation #67
metadata.description:
The Copenhagen Interpretation of quantum physics suggests that objects don't have physical properties until being observed.

In this generative piece by itsgalo and Spøgelsesmaskinen, a set of objects are being held in "superposition" and finally positioned when observed and minted.

Use mouse/touch to zoom, pan, and rotate. Press 's' to grab a screenshot. Best viewed in Firefox.

metadata.name: Fragmented Memory #9
metadata.description:
Our memory can interpret a single event in many different ways. Depending on time, or other factors, it evolves and can sometimes get corrupted. The same effect can also happen with our digital data.

The Fragmented Memory series highlights the correlation between human and computer memories and is a blend of human and AI-generated Artwork.

metadata.name: Castles #91
metadata.description:
I made 1B pixel art for the first time and I had a lot of fun doing it. Generally the majority of my fxHash drawings were PFPs, which I wanted to change it as well. You can also use Castles as phone backgrounds. Oh also there is no rarity in it, every drawing has same weight.

For screen shot, open it Castles in new tab via fxHash button. And press("S") to take (1152x2048) screen shot.

metadata.name: QUE DU BRUIT #16
metadata.description:
Pour créer cette proposition, j'ai utilisé du bruit VHS, en jouant avec la saturation et en supprimant certaines données pour créer des zones de transparence. 

Le bruit réfère à une poétique politique. Le vacarme est permanent. L'ordre et le silence, improbable.

*

J'utilise le code de PureSpider pour travailler les couches d'images.

metadata.name: Skyfloors #243
metadata.description:
Skyfloors are a study of perspective, occlusion, color, shape and motion. Occular meditation. A visceral demonstration of noise' ability to emulate natural systems; rolling hills, an angry sea, gentle breezes, crawling skin - all wrapped in 2d isometric projection with a flamboyant twist and a minimal nod to cel animation.

Controls:

right arrow - increase speed in direction 1
left arrow - increase speed in direction 0
P - pause / play
S - save image (increase res in devtools first if you are printing)
L - switch to black outline on brightlines featured pieces
B - switch to solid background on split background featured pieces
D - disable drop shadow

These pieces are pretty feature heavy and include a couple of ultra rare surprises.

All color palettes are procedurally generated, with each edition selecting for 1 of 4 different palette functions. 2 of these functions are open source and developed by meodai:
https://twitter.com/meodai
https://github.com/meodai

https://twitter.com/p4stoboy

metadata.name: Monsters of the Deep #30
metadata.description:
"What would an ocean be without a monster lurking in the dark? It would be like sleep without dreams." ‒ Werner Herzog

Mythological monsters like Leviathan, Tiamat, and Lotan have long inspired awe and fear in people’s hearts. I was inspired by these sublime monsters and wanted to evoke their haunting and otherworldly presence.

For this project, I used creative coding techniques to simulate the methods of monotype printmaking. This medium allows for a fluid and expressive approach to art-making perfectly suited for my vision of these mythological monsters. With this work, I’m bringing these ancient legends to life in a contemporary form, exploring their enduring power and beauty by combining modern techniques with one of the oldest forms of visual art. 

My goal is to arouse a sense of wonder and mystery, using color and abstract shapes to conjure up visions of these legendary monsters from the abyss. Whether you see them as terrifying beasts or beautiful creatures of legend, one thing is clear - these monsters will always remain part of our collective imagination.

Features:
-6 Types of Monsters (Leviathan, Lotan, Tiamat, Aspidochelone, Hydra, Charybdis)
-3 Frame Styles (Portrait, Landscape, Square)
-10 Color Palettes
-Hidden Jewels of the Sea

metadata.name: Syzers #327
metadata.description:
Syzers is a generative synthesizer project with sounds altered by Tone JS.

···· On Tuesday, May 17, unsold editions will be burned ····

Visually it consists of 16 layers, in which more than 350 elements are combined randomly, generating synthesizers with unique environments and landscapes.
As for the sound, 40 tracks were recorded with analog synthesizers that were then assigned to each of the modules. These, combined in groups of 4, provide thousands of possible combinations. 
In addition, these sounds will be further modified by code effects that will randomly vary their properties.

Click to listen to the sounds

Many thanks to @Jpupper and @Fipiaggio for help with programming the sound part and @Purespider for the template. 
"FXHASH PFP Token Generator" https://github.com/PureSpider/fxhash-pfp

for best resolution "open live" then use the "download image" button on the lower right corner ;)

metadata.name: Stitched: Trauma #243
metadata.description:
"Every happy family is alike; every unhappy family is unhappy in its own way." -- Tolstoy

Stitched: trauma is based on the same code, and premise, as Stitched, with one twist: childhood trauma distorts experiences and events; some are wildly chaotic; others obsessively retrace a few curves. It is an experiment in combinatorial complexity: are two mints ever indistinguishable? 

The distortion has been carefully designed to allow a huge space of legibly distinct possibilities.

controls:

mouse click or space bar: pause / unpause / reset animation
s: save current frame
f: toggle between square format and stretch aspect ratio
1-6: set pixel density
